#Initialize random number generator
random.seed(1)
#create array of values from 100 to 200 with a step of 500.
#These values will determine the number of MC simulations.
runs = np.arange (100,200000, 500)

#Question 3(i)
b= 3
a= 1
c =b-a 
#Exact solution
Exct3i= (1/3*(b**3)-(1/3*a))

sim_runs=[]; sim_result=[];closed_form =[]; price_diff=[]
for i in range(len(runs)):
    randset = pd.DataFrame(random.rand(runs[i])) 
    
        
    # MC Integral I = (b-a)* Expected [ f(U x (b-a) +a)]          
    I3i =  c*(np.average((randset*c+a)**2))
    
        
    # Modulus of Relative Difference
    diff = np.absolute(I3i/Exct3i-1)
    
    #Appending data into list 
    sim_runs.append(runs[i])
    closed_form.append(Exct3i)
    sim_result.append(I3i)
    price_diff.append(diff)
  
    
Agg_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Simulated runs':sim_runs, 'Closed-Form Solution': closed_form,
    'Simulated result': sim_result, 'Relative Diff between MC and Closed-Form': price_diff})

Agg_df

#Question 3(ii)

#Gaussian Integral
Exct3ii = ((np.pi)**0.5)/2

sim_runs2=[]; sim_result2=[];closed_form2 =[]; price_diff2=[]

for i in range(len(runs)):
    randsetii = pd.DataFrame(random.rand(runs[i])) 
    
    # (-1+1/U)**2
    nu_xii = (-1+1/randsetii)**2
    
    #g(nu_x)/(U*U)
    gii= np.exp(-nu_xii)/(randsetii*randsetii)
    
    # Expected [ g(nu_x)/(U*U)]
    I3ii =  average(gii)
          
    # Modulus of Relative Difference
    diff2 = np.absolute(I3ii/Exct3ii-1)
    
    #Appending data into list 
    sim_runs2.append(runs[i])
    closed_form2.append(Exct3ii)
    sim_result2.append(I3ii)
    price_diff2.append(diff2)
    
Agg_df2 = pd.DataFrame({
    'Simulated runs':sim_runs2, 'Closed-Form Solution': closed_form2,
    'Simulated result': sim_result2, 'Relative Diff between MC and Closed-Form': price_diff2})

Derivation for Exact Solution:

Calculation used in MC Integral

In [22]:
#Question 3(iii)

#Gaussian Integral
Exct3iii = 3 # derivation show above 

scalar3 =  6/sqrt(2*np.pi)

sim_runs3=[]; sim_result3=[];closed_form3 =[]; price_diff3=[]

for i in range(len(runs)):
    randsetiii = pd.DataFrame(random.rand(runs[i])) 
    
    # (-1+1/U)**2
    nu_xiii = -1+(1/randsetiii)
    
    #I= g(nu_x)/(U*U)
    g3iii= np.exp(-(nu_xiii*nu_xiii)/2)
    
    full3= g3iii/(randsetiii*randsetiii)
    
        
    # Expected [ g(nu_x)/(U*U)]
    I3iii =  scalar3*average(full3)
    
    # Modulus of Relative Difference
    diff3 = np.absolute(I3iii/Exct3iii-1)
    
    #Appending data into list 
    sim_runs3.append(runs[i])
    closed_form3.append(Exct3iii)
    sim_result3.append(I3iii)
    price_diff3.append(diff3)
    
Agg_df3 = pd.DataFrame({
    'Simulated runs':sim_runs3, 'Closed-Form Solution': closed_form3,
    'Simulated result': sim_result3, 'Relative Diff between MC and Closed-Form': price_diff3})

Observation 3(iii):

With reference to the chart above,relative difference of <1% can be observed, roughly after midway between 0-50k simulations.

Relative differences circa 0.5% can still be observed after 100k simulation.Further testing is definitely required, in order to discover the optimum number of simulation to gain assurance that the relative differences will consistently remain beneath the 0.5% threshold.

No additional simulations were conducted out of consideration for practicality and performance.

Conclusion: Based on the observation above, 100k runs of random simulation should be sufficient to run Monte Carlo Integration, barring a relative threshold of 1% (to the exact solution) and the user is indifferent towards the small difference in performance runtime.
